%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Quantification of Energy} 
\label{sec:Quantification_of_Energy}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

The literature shows three quantifications of energy ($E$) used in 
energy-augmented production functions: thermal energy ($Q$), 
exergy ($X$), and useful work ($U$). Thermal energy ($Q$) 
is the heat content of an energy carrier. Exergy ($X$) is 
the maximum useful work that could be extracted from an energy carrier 
by a process that brings the system into equilibrium with 
a heat reservoir, typically the surrounding environment 
\citep[p.~78]{Ayres:2010ug}. Like \citeauthor{Ayres:2010ug}, 
we use chemical exergy (as opposed to thermal exergy or mechanical exergy) 
as our quantification for exergy ($x$). Useful work ($U$) 
includes the direct energy that goes into an economy, including work 
from machines, human muscles, and animals. Firms pay for thermal energy ($Q$), 
but useful work ($U$) alters the size and shape of materials, 
keeps the lights on, and transports goods to consumers. 
Not all forms of energy are created equal in terms of their ability 
to generate economic activity \citep{Cleveland:2000vl, Warr:2010ht}. 
Both exergy ($X$), and to a greater extent, useful work ($U$) 
quantifications of energy are intended to account for the usefulness 
of energy for generating economic activity, thereby reflecting 
the ``quality'' of each energy type and the efficiency of machines 
and devices typically used in energy conversion processes.

Most energy economists use thermal energy ($q$) 
for the energy factor of production ($e$) in energy-augmented 
production functions, including \citet{Stern:2012ey}, 
\citet{Froling:2009vo}, \citet{Serrenho:2010vq}, and 
\citet{Kummel:1980wx,Kummel:1982vy,Kummel:1985vz,Kummel:1989tf,Kummel:2002tx,Kummel:2010vz}. 
\citet{Ayres:2003ec} introduced the idea that exergy ($x$) and 
useful work ($u$) were important factors of production. 

