%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Sources of Data}
\label{sec:Sources_of_Data}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

To assess energy-augmented models of economic growth along the 
coordinates of analysis outlined in Section~\ref{sec:Coordinates}, 
historical data for economic output ($Y$), capital stock ($K$), 
labor ($L$), thermal energy ($Q$), exergy ($X$), and useful work ($U$) 
are required. Subsections below describe sources for and calculations 
to obtain historical data. A final subsection presents the historical 
data in graphical form.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Economic Output} 
\label{sec:Economic_Output_Data}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

We measure economic output ($Y$) by gross domestic product (GDP). 
GDP data in real 2005 U.S. dollars for developed countries (1980--2011) 
and all other countries (1991--2011) was obtained from 
the World Bank's Global Economic Prospects (GEP) database 
\citep{WorldBankGEP:2013a}.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Capital Stock} 
\label{sec:Capital_Stock_Data}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Gross capital stock in real 2005 U.S. dollars 
for developed countries (1980--2011) and 
all other countries (1991--2011) was obtained from 
the World Bank's Global Economic Prospects (GEP) database 
\citep{WorldBankGEP:2013a}.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Labor and Employment}
\label{sec:Labor_Data}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Total employment and average hours worked per worker per year 
for the developed nations (United States, United Kingdom, and Japan) 
for 1980--2011 were obtained from the United States 
\citet[Tables 6 and 7]{BLS:2013a}. Total hours worked per year was 
calculated by multiplying total employment by average hours worked 
per worker per year.  

The World Bank's World Development Indicators database 
\citep{WorldBankWDI:2013a} provides the employment to population 
ratio for people fifteen and older, total population, and a percentage 
of people under fifteen for other economies (South Africa, China, Iran, 
Saudi Arabia, Tanzania, and Zambia) for 1991--2011. The population 
of people under fifteen years of age was subtracted from total population 
to calculate the population of people fifteen and older. 
Total employment was calculated by multiplying the employment to 
population ratio of people fifteen and older by the population 
of people fifteen and older.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Thermal Energy, Exergy, and Useful Work} 
\label{sec:Energy_Data}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

To account for all energy input to an economy, we summed consumption data 
for many energy sources, including coal, oil and petroleum products, 
dry natural gas and natural gas plant liquids, nuclear power generation, 
and renewable energy sources (solar, wind, geothermal, biomass/fuel wood, 
and hydro). In the style of work by Warr and Ayres 
\citep{Ayres:2003ec, Ayres:2005kn, Warr:2010ht, Warr:2010ga, Warr:2012cg}, 
energy from human and animal muscle power was also included. 
Similar to the economic data discussed in 
Sections~\ref{sec:Economic_Output_Data}--\ref{sec:Labor_Data}, 
we generated energy data for developed countries from 1980--2011, 
with the exception of useful work data (1980--2000). For all other countries, 
we generated thermal energy and exergy data for 1991--2011. 
Details on each energy quantifications are given in subsections below.

%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Thermal Energy} 
\label{sec:Q_Data}
%------------------------------

Thermal energy ($Q$) for fuels (in units of TJ/year) was calculated by

\begin{equation} \label{eq:thermal_energy}
  Q_{fuel} = C_{fuel}h_{fuel}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $C_{fuel}$ is the consumption rate of the fuel 
(in units of short tons/year for coal, barrels/year for oil and petroleum, 
ft$^3$/year for dry natural gas and natural gas plant liquids, 
and m$^3$/year for biomass/fuel wood) and $h_{{fuel}}$ is 
the heat content of the fuel (in kJ/short ton for coal, kJ/barrel for oil, 
kJ/ft$^3$ for dry natural gas and natural gas plant liquids, 
and kJ/kg for biomass/fuel wood). Fuel wood density of 300~kg/m$^3$ 
was taken from \citet{Ragland:2013wp} at the low end of the range 
of density of dry wood and bark.

Yearly consumption rates ($C_{fuel}$) of coal, oil and petroleum, 
dry natural gas and natural gas plant liquids, and biofuels 
(ethanol and biodiesel) were obtained from the \citet{EIA:2013a} 
for all economies. Yearly average heat content data for coal, oil, 
and natural gas and natural gas plant liquids was obtained from the 
EIA for all economies. We used lower (net) heating values of 
26.8~MJ/kg \citep[Table~A-27]{Cengel:2011ww} and 37.8~MJ/kg 
\citep[Table~7.3]{Gupta:2010vg} for the heat content of ethanol 
and corn-based biodiesel, respectively. Yearly consumption and 
heat content data for biomass/fuel wood was obtained from the 
``Fuelwood'' time series of the FAO Statistics Database 
\citep{FAO:2013a}.

For renewable and nuclear energy sources, yearly electricity 
generation (in BTU/year) was available directly from 
the \citet{EIA:2013a} for all economies, so 
Equation~\ref{eq:thermal_energy} was unnecessary.

Animal and human muscle work was estimated using an approach 
similar to \citet{Ayres:2010ug}, using some data from Warr's 
REXS database \citep{Warr:2012a} and results from 
\citet{Wirsenius:2000vi}. For animal work, our analysis was 
restricted to draught animals (horses and mules). Muscle work 
from animals ($Q_{animals}$) was calculated using

\begin{equation} \label{eq:animal_muscle}
  Q_{animals} = Q_{m,horse}N_{horses} + Q_{m,mule}N_{mules}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $Q_m$ is metabolizable energy (in kcal/day-animal) 
and $N$ is the number of animals. Metabolizable energy values 
($Q_{m,horses}$ = 19,110 kcal/day-horse and $Q_{m,mules}$ = 
7,215 kcal/day-mule) were taken from \citet{Warr:2012a}. 
$Q_m$ represents the amount of energy in the feed consumed by 
animals for a day of work, and they are assumed constant for 
all countries and years. The number of horses and mules for 
each economy was taken from the ``Live Animals'' section of the 
FAO Statistics online database \citep{FAO:2013a}.

Human muscle power was calculated in a similar manner:

\begin{equation} \label{eq:human_muscle}
  Q_{workers} = Q_{m,workers} N_{workers}
\end{equation}

\noindent where the value of $Q_{m,workers}$ is the ``the amount 
of food available for human consumption'' (i.e., at the wholesale level) 
taken from the 
\citet[``\texttt{Dietary~Energy~Cons.~Countries}'' tab]{FAO:2013b}. 
The value for $N_{workers}$ was obtained from the labor time series 
for each economy as discussed in Section~\ref{sec:Labor_Data}.

%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Exergy} 
\label{sec:X_Data}
%------------------------------

Exergy ($X$), expressed in TJ/year, was calculated by multiplying 
the thermal energy ($Q$) values discussed in Section~\ref{sec:Q_Data} 
by a unitless exergy-to-thermal-energy allocation factor 
($f_{exergy-allocation}$) shown in Table~\ref{tab:Exergy_Allocation}.

\begin{equation} \label{eq:exergy}
  X_{fuel} = f_{exergy-allocation} Q_{fuel}
\end{equation}

\begin{table} \caption{Exergy allocation factors.} \label{tab:Exergy_Allocation} 
  \begin{center}
    \begin{tabular}{r l} 
      Fuel                                    & $f_{exergy-allocation}$ \\
      \hline
      Coal                                    & 1.088    \\
      Oil and petroleum                       & 1.073   \\      
      Dry natural gas and                     & \multirow{2}{*}{1.04}    \\
      natural gas liquids                     &         \\
      Corn-based biodiesel                    & 1.07  \\
      Biomass/fuel wood                       & 1.15   \\
      Ethanol biofuel                         & 1.099 \\
      Nuclear, wind,                          & \multirow{2}{*}{1.0}   \\
      solar PV, and hydro                     &                        \\
    \end{tabular}
  \end{center}
\end{table}

\noindent For carbon-based energy sources, $f_{exergy-allocation}$ 
is the ratio of chemical exergy to lower (net) heating value. 
The exergy allocation factors for coal, oil, natural gas, 
biodiesel, and biomass/fuel wood were obtained from 
\citet[Table~A-2]{Ayres:2003ec}. The exergy allocation ratio for 
liquid ethanol was calculated from the standard molar chemical exergy 
of 1357.7~kJ/mol \citep[Table~II]{Szargut:1988wv} and its lower 
(net) heating value of 26.8~MJ/kg \citep[Table~A-27]{Cengel:2011ww}. 
$f_{exergy-allocation}$ for each fuel was assumed to be constant 
through time across all economies. For nuclear, wind, 
solar photovoltaic, and hydro energy sources, the electricity generated 
is already pure exergy, so $f_{exergy-allocation}$ is unity.

To calculate the exergy of animal and human muscle power, 
the food-to-work conversion efficiency ($\eta_{food \rightarrow work}$) 
and the ratio of food intake to food available at wholesale 
($f_{intake/wholesale}$) were included. 

\begin{equation} \label{eq:animal_muscle_exergy}
  X_{animals} = \eta_{food \rightarrow work,animals} Q_{animals}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation} \label{eq:human_muscle_exergy}
  X_{workers} = \eta_{food \rightarrow work,workers} f_{intake/wholesale} Q_{workers}
\end{equation}

\noindent $\eta_{food \rightarrow work, animals}$ and 
$\eta_{food \rightarrow work, workers}$ are animal and worker efficiency 
of converting food into energy, respectively. The animal feed-to-work 
conversion efficiency ($\eta_{feed \rightarrow work, animals}$ = 0.4) 
was taken from \citet{Warr:2012a} and assumed equal across all economies. 
The food-to-work efficiency for workers 
($\eta_{food \rightarrow work, workers}$ = 0.2) was taken from 
\citet[Table~B.1]{Ayres:2010ug}. Following \citet[p.~315]{Ayres:2010ug} 
and methodology from \citet{Warr:2012a}, an additional factor 
($f_{intake/wholesale}$) was included to account for ``wastage and 
losses of food in the household, e.g. during storage, in preparation 
and cooking, as plate-waste, or quantities fed to domestic animals 
and pets'' \citep[\texttt{notes} tab]{FAO:2013b}. 
Values of $f_{intake/wholesale}$ were calculated from 
\citet[Table~3.3 for wholesale and Table~3.4 for intake]{Wirsenius:2000vi}. 
$f_{intake/wholesale}$ varies by country as shown in 
Table~\ref{tab:f_intake_wholesale}. A similar intake-to-wholesale ratio 
could also be applied to animal work, but data to calculate the ratio was 
unavailable from \citet{Wirsenius:2000vi}, and $f_{intake/wholesale,animals}$ 
is assumed to be unity.\footnote{The error in total exergy input to 
any economy caused by assuming $f_{intake/wholesale,animals} = 1.0$ 
is very small, because animal muscle exergy is a small fraction of the 
total exergy supply to any economy, with a maximum of 0.41\% for China in 1992. 
It could also be argued that $f_{intake/wholesale, animals}$ is likely 
to be closer to unity than $f_{intake/wholesale, workers}$.}

