%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Useful Work} 
\label{sec:U_Data}
%------------------------------

The conversion of a raw energy carrier (e.g., coal) into 
productive energy for an economy (e.g., electricity) necessarily 
involves inefficiencies. In the case of coal consumption, 
only about one-third of the coal exergy is converted to useful electricity: 
the rest is waste heat. The concept of ``useful work,'' pioneered by 
Ayres and Warr \citep{Ayres:2003ec, Ayres:2005kn}, builds upon 
exergy analysis to consider efficiencies of both energy production and enduse. 
To calculate useful work ($U$), the total exergy input to an 
economy ($X$) is decomposed into several end uses: 
high temperature industrial heat (e.g., steel production), 
medium temperature heat (e.g., steam production), 
low temperature space heat (for residential heating), 
mechanical drive (energy used for prime mover engines of all types except electric motors), 
electricity (excluding lighting), 
lighting (from both electricity and fuels), and 
muscle work (from animals and workers) as shown in the following equation:

\begin{equation} \label{eq:useful_work}
  U = \sum_i{\varepsilon_i \phi_i X}
\end{equation}

\noindent where the subscript $i$ indicates the energy enduse, 
$\varepsilon_i$ is the efficiency of converting exergy into 
useful energy for each enduse, and $\phi_i$ gives 
the fraction of exergy input to an economy that goes toward 
the $i^\mathrm{th}$ enduse.

Values of $\varepsilon_i$ and $\phi_i$ were calculated from 
the REXS database supplied by \citet{Warr:2012a}. 
Values of $X$ were calculated by methods discussed in 
Section~\ref{sec:X_Data}. For most countries, values of 
$\phi_i$ are not constant with time, as economic sectors with 
different distributions of raw exergy inputs grow at different rates. 
\citeapos{Warr:2012a} REXS database contains information for 
developed economies (United States, United Kingdom, and Japan) 
from 1900--2000, and we used data from the 1980--2000 timeframe. 
Extending the REXS database to the BRICS, petrol, and LDC economies 
is beyond the scope of this work, because longitudinal data for 
the efficiency of different end uses ($\varepsilon_i$) and 
the distribution of exergy sources to end uses 
($\phi_i$) are extremely difficult to obtain.

