%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Parameter Estimation}
\label{sec:Parameter_Estimation}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Each of the economic growth models discussed in 
Section~\ref{sec:Prod_Func_Forms} has parameters which must be estimated 
for each economy (see Section~\ref{sec:Economy_Types}) and 
each energy quantification (see Section~\ref{sec:Quantification_of_Energy}) 
via least-squares methods. The following subsections discuss 
parameter estimation methods and interpret the results. 

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Cobb-Douglas Models}
\label{sec:CD_Parameter_Estimation}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

The Cobb-Douglas model without energy is given by 
Equation~\ref{eq:CD}. The Cobb-Douglas production function was
reparameterized as

\begin{equation} \label{eq:CD_reparam}
  y = A k^{\alpha} l^{1-\alpha}; A = \mathrm{e}^{\lambda (t-t_0)}
\end{equation}

\noindent to ensure $\alpha + \beta = 1$ for constant returns to scale. 
$\lambda$ and $\alpha$ were estimated by the 
\texttt{R} \citep{R} function \texttt{nls}. 
If the estimated value for $\alpha$ was found outside the interval $[0,1]$, 
we set $\alpha$ to its boundary value and re-estimated $\lambda$. 
The value of $\beta$ was found with $\beta = 1 - \alpha$. 

Figure~\ref{fig:CD_Cloud_Graph} shows $\alpha$, $\beta$, and $\gamma$ parameter values for resample models for the Cobb-Douglas model (without energy). $\gamma$ is always 0.0, because energy is not included in this model.

