To estimate the parameters $\lambda$, $\alpha$, $\beta$, and $\gamma$ 
in the energy-augmented Cobb-Douglas model, Equation~\ref{eq:CDe} 
was reparameterized as

\begin{equation} \label{eq:CDe_AB_reparam}
  y = A k^{\min(a,b)} l^{|b-a|} e^{1 - \max(a,b)}; A = \mathrm{e}^{\lambda (t-t_0)}
\end{equation}

\noindent with 
$\alpha = \min(a,b)$, 
$\beta = |b-a|$, and 
$\gamma = 1 - \max(a,b)$.
The reparameterization ensures that $\alpha + \beta + \gamma = 1$. 
The \texttt{R} \citep{R} function \texttt{nls} was used to estimate 
values of $\lambda$, $a$, and $b$.
If the fitted value for $a$ ($b$) fell outside $[0,1]$, it was 
set equal to its boundary value and $\lambda$ and $b$ ($a$) 
were re-estimated.

To demonstrate the characteristics of the parameter estimation process, 
we performed a grid search over values of $\gamma$, 
wherein we re-estimated values of $\lambda$, $\alpha$, and 
$\beta$ at each value of $\gamma$. 
Figure~\ref{fig:CDeGridLattice} shows the sum of squared errors ($SSE$), 
$\alpha$, and $\beta$ as a function of the fixed value of 
$\gamma$ with thermal energy ($q$). 

