Figure~\ref{fig:CDeGridLattice} shows that, for most economies,
the minimum $SSE$ occurs at or near a boundary of 
$\alpha$, $\beta$, or $\gamma$. 
The parameter estimation algorithm (\texttt{nls}) had difficulty converging when
the optimal value for the parameter represented by the absolute value function 
(in Equation~\ref{eq:CDe_AB_reparam}, $\beta$) 
was near a boundary. If the absolute value caused non-convergence of the 
\texttt{nls} function, second and, if necessary, third reparameterizations 
were attempted:

\begin{equation} \label{eq:CDe_CD_reparam}
  y = A k^{1 - \max(c,d)} l^{\min(c,d)} e^{|d-c|}; A = \mathrm{e}^{\lambda (t-t_0)}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation} \label{eq:CDe_FG_reparam}
  y = A k^{|g-f|} l^{1 - \max(f,g)} e^{\min(f,g)}; A = \mathrm{e}^{\lambda (t-t_0)}
\end{equation}

\noindent If none of the three reparameterizations converged, 
the parameterization with the smallest $SSE$
was used. \ref{sec:Convergence_Resample_Models} shows the 
fraction of unconverged models for each model type. The above approach
resulted in very few unconverged resample models, 
even with \Sexpr{numResamples()} resamples.

