%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Implications}
\label{sec:Implications}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

**** This section needs to be re-evaluated after the statistical work is 
tightened up during Summer 2013. ****

The above analysis points to several implications.

\begin{itemize}
  \item{The use of chemical exergy, as opposed to thermal energy, 
        in economic growth models is probably unnecessary. 
        Table~\ref{tab:Exergy_Allocation} shows that exergy allocation factors are 
        all close to unity. 
        Therefore, there is a small difference in absolute magnitude 
        between $Q$ and $X$. 
        However, there is no difference in indexed magnitude 
        between $q$ and $x$, unless there are large changes 
        in energy mix for an economy. 
        Figure~\ref{fig:Historical_Lattice_Graph} shows that 
        $q$ and $x$ lines lie atop one another for almost every economy.}
  \item{The concept of useful work ($u$) is potentially useful and 
        should be explored beyond developed economies. 
        Figure~\ref{fig:Historical_Lattice_Graph} shows that $u$ grows 
        at very different rates from thermal energy ($q$) or exergy ($x$). 
        Useful work may contain different information from thermal energy and exergy.}
  \item{Figure~\ref{fig:CDeGridLattice} shows that the set 
        of parameters ($\lambda$, $\alpha$, $\beta$, and $\gamma$) that 
        minimizes $SSE$ for the energy-augmented Cobb-Douglas production function 
        always (with the exception of Saudi Arabia) has 
        $\beta = 0$ or $\gamma = 0$. 
        This result implies that it is unnecessary to include both labor ($l$) 
        and energy ($e$) in the Cobb-Douglas production function.}
  \item{Partial residual plots for both the Cobb-Douglas model 
        (Figures~\ref{fig:CDPartialResidualsQ}--\ref{fig:CDPartialResidualsU} and 
        CES model (Figures~\ref{fig:CESPartialResidualsQ}--\ref{fig:CESPartialResidualsU}) 
        indicate that augmenting the Cobb-Douglas and CES production functions 
        with energy is not beneficial.}
  \item{Figure~\ref{fig:CIvsParam_Lattice_Graph} shows that important energy parameters 
        for both the energy-augmented Cobb-Douglas and CES production functions 
        ($\gamma$ and $\delta$, respectively) have large confidence intervals such that 
        we are unable to say (at the 95\% confidence level) that energy is 
        an important factor for economic growth, 
        vis-\`{a}-vis capital stock ($k$) or labor ($l$) for most economies.}
  \item{Figure~\ref{fig:CIvsParam_Lattice_Graph} indicates that 
        energy (in all quantifications: $q$, $x$, and $u$) is complementary 
        to capital stock ($k$) and labor ($l$) for producing economic growth, 
        according to the CES model.}
  \item{Figures~\ref{fig:LINEXq_Params_Graph}--\ref{fig:LINEXu_Params_Graph} 
        indicate that LINEX model fitting parameters $a_0$ and $c_t$ are 
        significant (at the 95\% confidence level) for nearly all countries. 
        Figure~\ref{fig:LINEX_GDP_Lattice_Graph} shows that 
        the LINEX production function provides reasonably good fits 
        to historical data. 
        This evidence indicates that the LINEX production function 
        (with energy ($e$) as its only factor of production) is 
        a reasonable replacement for the Cobb-Douglas and CES production functions 
        which have capital stock ($k$) and labor ($l$) as factors of production.}
  \item{**** Discuss the AIC values for each of the model types. 
        It could happen that the LINEX models have a higher AIC value than 
        the CD or CES models. 
        If so, that would mean that the LINEX model is actually preferred 
        to the CD or CES models, primarily because it does a good-enough job 
        of predicting economic output with fewer adjustable parameters (2) 
        compared to CD (2), CDe (3), CES (4), CESe (6). 
        Discuss with Randy Pruim during Summer 2013. ****}
\end{itemize}

The evidence above leads to a re-conceptualization of the relationships 
among energy, capital stock, and labor: energy is \emph{embedded within} 
capital stock and labor, and, therefore, it is both 
unwarranted and unnecessary to include \emph{both} energy ($e$) 
and the capital stock/labor pair ($kl$) in a production function. 
The empirical evidence indicates that \emph{both} 
(a) capital stock/labor production functions (Cobb-Douglas and CES without energy) and 
(b) an energy-only production function (LINEX) provide a reasonable models for economic growth.

