\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:Conclusion}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

**** Edit conclusion after we finish the statistical studies. ****

We claim that statistical properties (e.g., covariances) 
of historical economic data and statistical properties 
(e.g., confidence intervals) of production function fitting parameters are 
extremely useful for interpreting historical economic data and growth model results. 
We know of no previous studies on the role of energy in the economy that 
presented these statistical properties, 
and we presume that energy-augmentation of production functions has been done 
in the literature without regard to whether it is statistically meaningful to do so. 
That different authors can find good correlation 
between model predictions and historical data 
with very different growth model coefficients is 
a result of the heretofore unseen large confidence intervals 
on the fitting parameters. 
As a consequence, economic growth models that assume very different relationships 
among capital stock, labor, and energy can all be successful in matching historical data. 
In short, the production function becomes a canvas upon which 
investigators can paint their preconceived vision of the importance 
(or not) of energy for economic growth.

To break free from this problem, a new way of conceptualizing 
the relationships among capital stock, labor, and energy is required. 
Our analysis above indicates that energy is unequivocally complementary 
to the capital stock/labor pair for many types of economies. 
We agree with K\"{u}mmel that energy is required 
to form and maintain capital stock, and that energy is required to sustain labor. 
(And, for that matter, we agree that labor is required to operate capital stock.) 
In other words, energy is already, always \emph{embedded within} capital stock and labor. 
We posit that the complementarity between ($kl$) and ($e$) shown 
by the energy-augmented CES production function is due 
to the embeddedness of energy within the traditional factors of production, 
capital stock and labor.

The foregoing discussion means that production functions with either 
(a) energy only (such as the LINEX model) or 
(b) capital stock/labor only (such as the Cobb-Douglas and CES models without energy) 
can both be successful in predicting economic growth. 
But, the embedded nature of energy in capital stock and labor means that 
augmenting a capital stock/labor only production function 
with energy is redundant and unnecessary, and, therefore, unwarranted.


