We begin by fitting single-factor economic models of the form

\begin{equation} \label{eq:Single_Factor_Generic}
  y = \mathrm{e}^{\lambda (t-t_0)}f^{m}
\end{equation}

\noindent to historical data where the factor of production ($f$) is 
one of $k$, $l$, $q$, $x$, or $u$, and 
the exponent ($m$) is $\alpha$ for $k$, $\beta$ for $l$, 
or $\gamma$ for $q$, $x$, and $u$.

Coefficients derived from resampling are shown in 
Figures~\ref{fig:SFk_Resample_Graph}--\ref{fig:SFu_Resample_Graph}. 
In each case, the exponent on the factor of production is assumed to be $m = 1$.

<<SFk_Resample_Graph, fig.pos="H", fig.width=ninePanelGraphWidth, fig.height=ninePanelGraphHeight, fig.cap="Single factor model (with $f = k$ and $m = \\alpha$) resampling results.">>=
